The architecture separates pure layout math (`tree.rs`, `state.rs`) from X11 event handling (`wm.rs`) and software rendering (`render.rs`). An arena-keyed n-ary tree (`NodeId` → `HashMap<NodeId, Node>`) keeps splits n-ary so collapsing a leaf redistributes its ratio proportionally to siblings rather than forcing a binary rebalance; `theme.rs` is the single source of truth for all palette and metric constants, while `state.rs` owns every mutation (split, close, resize, tab cycle, scroll, canvas width, insert-at-root, boundary resize, tab-move-to-sibling) so the event loop in `wm.rs` never touches the tree directly. Layout-changing actions trigger a wall-clock-driven ease-out-back animation (~280 ms) that interpolates frame rects with freshly created leaves starting from a collapsed sliver, with pre-split frame positions carried forward so content slides from its old spot. A single full-screen underlay window composites the optional `SPLITWM_WALLPAPER` PNG, all leaf chrome (tab bars, focus borders, content panels), gap drag handles, and "+" insert buttons—including edge insert buttons at the far left and right of the canvas—below every client via chunked `PutImage`, avoiding any compositing-manager dependency; `arrange()` dynamically grows the canvas width from leaf count and minimum split width, positions/represents the active client into each frame, maps off-screen frames out, and resamples the focused client's top-center pixel content to adopt its accent colour (skipped mid-drag to avoid redundant X round-trips). A `smush` system synthesizes Ctrl+0/Ctrl+- keystrokes via XTEST to auto-shrink terminal fonts in narrow splits, cached per client and width bucket; consecutive motion events within a batch are coalesced to the most recent pointer position so drag recomposites never pile up, and the full-screen BGRX blit buffer is reused across frames via a `RefCell<Vec<u8>>` to avoid per-frame allocation. Tab bars use slanted trapezoid paths rendered with tiny-skia, with per-tab app icons fetched from `_NET_WM_ICON` and letter-glyph fallbacks rasterized via fontdue.
