PROJECT OVERVIEW:
**splitwm** is a standalone X11 tiling window manager in Rust that replicates the terminal-multiplexer-style split layout of a Lua-based AwesomeWM config.

The architecture separates pure layout math (`tree.rs`, `state.rs`) from X11 event handling (`wm.rs`) and software rendering (`render.rs`). An arena-keyed n-ary tree (`NodeId` → `HashMap<NodeId, Node>`) keeps splits n-ary so collapsing a leaf redistributes its ratio proportionally to siblings; `theme.rs` is the single source of truth for all palette and metric constants, while `state.rs` owns every mutation (split, close, resize, tab cycle, scroll, canvas width, insert-at-root, boundary resize, tab-move-to-sibling, move-client-to-leaf, toggle-minimize, swap-leaves) so the event loop in `wm.rs` never touches the tree directly. A cascading application launcher menu (`menu.rs`) scans freedesktop `.desktop` entries into categorized `MenuTree` data; per-leaf "+" buttons open this launcher anchored below the leaf, and root-level "+" buttons at inter-column boundaries insert new empty columns via `insert_at_root`. Tabs can be drag-and-dropped between leaves via pointer press/release tracking. The four split-control buttons on each leaf's tab bar (close, split, swap, minimize) are right-clickable to toggle the split direction; the swap button enables a two-click leaf-swap workflow, and the minimize button collapses a leaf to a minimal sliver while preserving its client. Edge insert buttons sit at the far left and right of the canvas. A bottom taskbar holds windows displaced from splits, rendered as icon tiles and clickable to re-insert them. Layout-changing actions trigger a wall-clock-driven ease-out-back animation (~280 ms) that interpolates frame rects with freshly created leaves starting from a collapsed sliver, with pre-split frame positions carried forward so content slides from its old spot. A single full-screen underlay window composites the optional `SPLITWM_WALLPAPER` PNG, all leaf chrome (tab bars with per-tab app icons from `_NET_WM_ICON` or letter-glyph fallbacks via fontdue, focus borders, content panels), gap drag handles, "+" insert buttons, split-control buttons, the bottom taskbar, and the launcher menu columns via chunked `PutImage`, avoiding any compositing-manager dependency; `arrange()` dynamically grows the canvas width from leaf count and minimum split width, positions/maps off-screen clients out, and resamples the focused client's top-center pixel content to adopt its accent colour (skipped mid-drag to avoid redundant X round-trips). A `smush` system synthesizes Ctrl+0/Ctrl+- keystrokes via XTEST to auto-shrink terminal fonts in narrow splits, cached per client and width bucket. Consecutive motion events within a batch are coalesced to the most recent pointer position so drag recomposites never pile up, and the full-screen BGRX blit buffer is reused across frames via a `RefCell<Vec<u8>>` to avoid per-frame allocation. The launcher menu is implemented as two override-redirect popup windows (main column + one category submenu) with hover tracking, highlighted rows, and separator dividers, all composited through the same `draw_menu` renderer and `PutImage` blit path.
